{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:25:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1035"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1035"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.77,0.09,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33943"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1035"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1035"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19204"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4137"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8504"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/33943"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man attends for review one month after undergoing a radical prostatectomy for carcinoma of the prostate. His only complaint is persistent incontinence of urine, which occurs when he strains, coughs or sneezes. He uses about two incontinence pads a day. He does not have any other urinary symptoms. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes, for which he takes perindopril and metformin. His BMI is 26. His blood pressure is 136/82 mmHg, pulse 80/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. The physical examination is unremarkable. Nothing abnormal is found on urinalysis and he has a post-void residual volume of 40 ml.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Artificial urinary sphincter","Pelvic floor exercises","Oxybutynin","Prazosin","Urethral sling"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMen can expect to have some degree of stress incontinence while recovering from radical prostatectomy. Incontinence is expected during early recovery while the pelvic floor muscles adjust. By six weeks post-prostatectomy, only 10% of men wear a safety pad, and at one year, less than 1% of men have persisting incontinence requiring an artificial urinary sphincter to be placed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the first instance conservative measures should be promoted. \u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic floor exercises\u003C/strong\u003E (Kegel) should be done at least three times a day and this will lead to return of continence for 90% of patients within 12 months of surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrazosin is an alpha1 adrenergic receptor antagonist and used in cases of bladder neck outflow obstruction. Its use in post-prostatectomy stress incontinence could aggravate the symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxybutynin is an antimuscarinic agent that can be if the patient has an overactive bladder and urge incontinence, where the drug will reduce involuntary bladder contractions. Oxybutynin does not have a role in stress incontinence unless there was evidence of bladder over-activity. Because of their side effects (dry mouth, constipation, drowsiness), these agent are not tolerated well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA urethral sling  or artificial urinary sphincter may be considered if a 12 month period of conservative treatment has not provided any symptomatic improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Stress incontinence is a common post-prostatectomy complication and most cases can be treated effectively with pelvic floor exercises."],"references":["Rahnama MS, Marcelissen T, Geavlete B, et al.Current Management of Post-radical Prostatectomy Urinary Incontinence. Front Surg 2021; 8:103389."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19204"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1035"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"19204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/19204"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-03-23T11:12:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-03-23T11:12:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1035"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"33943"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t